Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888500033&r=1&w=2">The US domain</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000019&r=1&w=2">Rob Austein &lt;SRA () XX ! LCS ! MIT ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198702">1987-02-27 13:50:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926778&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926778&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Might I suggest that CNAME entries be added to the US zone so that
people will be able to win with a name like XX.LCS.MIT.EDU.US if they
want to type out all of that.  Ie, to use your analogy, it should not
be illegal to use "USA" in a domestic letter, and at the moment even
mail from outside will lose if it tries.

If this wasn't clear, what I was proposing was just about ten entries,
eg:

COM.US.	IN CNAME COM.
EDU.US. IN CNAME EDU.

etc.

Right now all that's in the US zone is 50 HINFO records for the States
of the union and a couple of joke entries for ISI.

If Canada wants to be part of the DDN/ARPANET COM/EDU/MIL/whatever
setup, they can add the same kind of CNAMEs to the CA (or CAN) zone.

--Rob

